#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:1
msgid "General Guidelines"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:3
msgid "Names"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:5
msgid "Be descriptive (`descriptive-names`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:7
msgid ""
"Choose names that convey meaning at the point of use. Avoid single-letter "
"names and ambiguous abbreviations. Prefer full words over cryptic shorthand "
"so that readers do not need surrounding context to understand a variable's "
"purpose. Prefer names that are as short as possible while still being "
"unambiguous at the point of use."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:15
msgid "Be accurate (`accurate-names`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:17
msgid ""
"Avoid confusing names. If a name can be misread to imply the wrong meaning, "
"behavior, or side effects, it must be corrected immediately."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:23
msgid "// Good — clearly a count\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:24
msgid ""
"// Bad — looks like a collection\n"
"// rather than a numeric counter\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:30
msgid "Choose verbs that reflect the actual work being done."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:34
msgid "// Good — implies a MMIO read is involved\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:35
#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:37
#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:44
#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:46
msgid "/* .. */"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:36
msgid "// Bad — looks like a plain field access\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:43
msgid "// Good — implies an O(n) collection pass\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:45
msgid "// Bad — sounds like an accessor returning a reference\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:50
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#1488](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"pull/1488#discussion_r1825441287) and [\\#2964](https://github.com/asterinas/"
"asterinas/pull/2964#discussion_r2789739882)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:54
msgid "Encode units and important attributes in names (`encode-units`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:56
msgid ""
"When the type does not encode the unit, the name must. Kernel code deals "
"with bytes, pages, frames, nanoseconds, ticks, and sectors — ambiguous units "
"are a source of real bugs."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:62
msgid ""
"```text\n"
"// Good — unit is unambiguous\n"
"timeout_ns\n"
"offset_bytes\n"
"size_pages\n"
"delay_ms\n"
"\n"
"// Bad — unit is ambiguous\n"
"timeout\n"
"offset\n"
"size\n"
"delay\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:76
msgid ""
"Where the language's type system can enforce units (e.g., newtypes), prefer "
"that. Where it cannot, the name must carry the information."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:80
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2796](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"pull/2796#discussion_r2646889913)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:83
msgid "Use assertion-style boolean names (`bool-names`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:85
msgid ""
"Boolean variables and functions should read as assertions of fact. Use "
"`is_`, `has_`, `can_`, `should_`, `was_`, or `needs_` prefixes. Never use "
"negated names (`is_not_empty`, `no_error`); prefer the positive form "
"(`is_empty`, `ok` or `succeeded`). A bare name like `found`, `done`, or "
"`ready` is acceptable when the context is unambiguous."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:97
msgid "// Good — reads as an assertion\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:101
msgid "// Bad — verb suggests an action, not a query\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:103
msgid "// Bad — negated name\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:108
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#1488](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"pull/1488#discussion_r1841827039)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:111
msgid "Comments"
msgstr "註釋"

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:113
msgid "Prefer semantic line breaks (`semantic-line-breaks`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:115
msgid ""
"For prose in Markdown and doc comments, insert line breaks at semantic "
"boundaries so each line carries one coherent idea. At minimum, break at "
"sentence boundaries. For longer sentences, also consider breaking at clause "
"boundaries."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:121
msgid ""
"Semantic line breaks make diffs smaller, reviews easier, and merge conflicts "
"less noisy."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:125
msgid ""
"As an exception, RFC documents that are mostly read-only can use regular "
"paragraph wrapping."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:129
msgid "See also: [Semantic Line Breaks](https://sembr.org/)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:132
msgid "Explain why, not what (`explain-why`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:134
msgid ""
"Comments should explain the intent behind the code, not restate what the "
"code does. If a comment merely paraphrases the code, it adds noise without "
"insight."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:139
msgid ""
"If a comment is needed to explain what code does, first try to rewrite the "
"code. Do not write good comments to compensate for bad code — rewrite it to "
"be straightforward."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:144
msgid ""
"See also: _The Art of Readable Code_, Chapter 6 \"Knowing What to Comment\"; "
"PR [\\#2265](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"pull/2265#discussion_r2266220943) and [\\#2050](https://github.com/asterinas/"
"asterinas/pull/2050#discussion_r2224106025)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:149
msgid "Document design decisions (`design-decisions`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:151
msgid ""
"When the code makes a non-obvious choice — a particular data structure, a "
"locking strategy, a deviation from Linux behavior — add a comment explaining "
"the rationale and any alternatives considered. Design-decision comments "
"(\"director's commentary\") are the most valuable kind of comment."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:160
msgid ""
"// We use a radix tree rather than a HashMap\n"
"// because lookups must be O(log n) worst-case\n"
"// for the page fault handler.\n"
"// A HashMap gives O(1) amortized\n"
"// but O(n) worst-case due to rehashing,\n"
"// which is unacceptable on the page fault path.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:168
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2265](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"pull/2265#discussion_r2266220943) and [\\#2050](https://github.com/asterinas/"
"asterinas/pull/2050#discussion_r2224106025)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:172
msgid "Cite specifications and algorithm sources (`cite-sources`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:174
msgid ""
"When implementing behavior defined by an external specification or a non-"
"trivial algorithm, cite the source: the relevant POSIX section, Linux man "
"page, hardware reference manual, or academic paper."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:181
msgid ""
"/// Maximum number of bytes guaranteed to be written to a pipe atomically.\n"
"///\n"
"/// For more details, see the description of `PIPE_BUF` in\n"
"/// <https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man7/pipe.7.html>.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:188
msgid "Layout"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:190
msgid "One concept per file (`one-concept-per-file`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:192
msgid ""
"When a file grows long or contains multiple distinct concepts, split it. "
"Each major data structure, each subsystem entry point, each significant "
"abstraction deserves its own file."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:198
msgid "Organize code for top-down reading (`top-down-reading`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:200
msgid ""
"A source file should read from top to bottom. Start with high-level entry "
"points and core flow. Move implementation details downward so readers can "
"understand the big picture first before diving into low-level helpers."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:206
msgid ""
"Within each visibility group (e.g., a module), order methods so that callers "
"appear before callees where possible, enabling the file to be read top to "
"bottom. Place public methods before private helpers."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:211
msgid "Group statements into logical paragraphs (`logical-paragraphs`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:213
msgid ""
"Within functions, group related statements into logical paragraphs separated "
"by blank lines. Each paragraph should represent one sub-step of the "
"function's overall purpose."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:219
msgid ""
"For long functions, add a one-line summary comment at the start of each "
"paragraph when the paragraph intent is not obvious."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:224
msgid "Formatting"
msgstr "格式化"

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:226
msgid "Format error messages consistently (`error-message-format`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:228
msgid ""
"Start with a lowercase letter (unless the first word is a proper noun or "
"identifier). Be specific: prefer \"`len` is too large\" over \"the argument "
"is invalid\"."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:233
msgid ""
"For system call errors, follow the style and descriptions in Linux man pages."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:236
msgid "API Design"
msgstr "API 設計"

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:238
msgid "Stick to familiar conventions (`familiar-conventions`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:240
msgid ""
"Prefer names and API shapes that users already know from Rust and Linux. Do "
"not invent new terms for well-known operations."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:246
msgid "// Good — follows common Rust naming conventions\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:249
msgid "// Bad — unfamiliar synonyms for common operations\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:255
msgid ""
"See also: [Least Surprise](../how-guidelines-are-written.md#least-surprise)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:258
msgid "Hide implementation details (`hide-impl-details`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:260
msgid ""
"Do not expose internal implementation details through public APIs (including "
"their documentation). A module's public surface should contain only what its "
"consumers need."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:265
msgid ""
"See also: [Modules and Crates](../rust-guidelines/language-items/modules-and-"
"crates.md#narrow-visibility) for Rust-specific visibility rules; PR [\\#2951]"
"(https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2951#discussion_r2786925410)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:270
msgid "Validate at boundaries, trust internally (`validate-at-boundaries`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:272
msgid ""
"Designate certain interfaces as validation boundaries. In Asterinas, syscall "
"entry points are the primary boundary: all user-supplied data (pointers, "
"file descriptors, sizes, flags, strings) must be validated at the syscall "
"boundary. Once validated, internal kernel functions may trust these values "
"without re-validation."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:281
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2806](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2806)."
msgstr ""
